I suggest to use ..= (or ...=) in place of the keywords &#x27;wait for&#x27;, and &#x27;from&#x27;. Less words, and &#x27;...&#x27; traditionally means &#x27;to be continued&#x27;, or &#x27;wait for a while&#x27;.<p>For this Kal code:<p><pre><code>  task getUserFriends (userName)
    wait for user from db.users.findOne {name:userName}
    wait for friends from db.friends.find {userId:user.id}
    return friends
</code></pre>
would become:<p><pre><code>  task getUserFriends (userName)
    user ..= db.users.findOne {name:userName}
    friends ..= db.friends.find {userId:user.id}
    return friends</code></pre>

JSON is probably a better format for describing data, but maybe not for document markup. Take the following code snipit:<p><pre><code>  <p class=&quot;justify&quot;><strong>hello</strong> world</p>
</code></pre>
How would you represent this in JSON? Here is my guess.<p><pre><code>  {
    node: &quot;paragraph&quot;,
    attributes: [{
      class: &quot;justify&quot;
    }],
    children: [{
      node: &quot;strong&quot;,
      content: &quot;hello&quot;
    },{
      node: &quot;text&quot;,
      content: &quot;world&quot;
    }]
  }
</code></pre>
There is a few things to note between these two examples.<p>In the XML version it is much easier to distinguish the actual content from the meta data. Right away we can see the p tag describing the content &quot;hello world&quot; with metadata as class/justify.<p>Also, since webpages are all text (we can view this as there is no data type) JSON may become less valuable. We don&#x27;t really describe types well in XML, but that shouldn&#x27;t matter on a webpage since it is only text. Where as in a data serialization format, like JSON, that sort of thing is extremely important.<p>I don&#x27;t feel strongly about XML, but I don&#x27;t think I want to use the same format for describing data as I do to describe my documents.
